							<p>By Jenny Shank, 8-11-05</p>
			
			
							A friend of mine recently moved from a nondescript Boulder condo to a lovely old house in nearby Louisville, and ever since then heâ€™s been talking up his new town and disparaging the old town.  He claims that people are friendlier in Louisvilleâ€”heâ€™s already met all of his neighbors, and one brought him a homemade cherry tart. Louisville people are more down-to-earth, he says, thereâ€™s less traffic and there are fewer annoying, idle rich tooling around on their expensive bicycles.  Sure, he admits, people arenâ€™t as beautiful in Louisville, but theyâ€™re much nicer to be around.  When <i>Money</i> magazine recently named Louisville the <a target="_blank" href="http://money.cnn.com/best/bplive/" title="fifth best place in America to live">fifth best place in America to live</a>, he crowed.  But as far as best titles go, Boulder has the market cornered.  <br />
<br />
This year alone, the Denver-Boulder metro area was named the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.forbes.com/home/singles/2005/07/25/singles-best-cities_cx_05sing_0725land.html" title="Best City for Singles">Best City for Singles</a> by <i>Forbes</i> magazine, Boulder was listed at number six in <i>The 100 Best Art Towns in America</i> by critic John Villani, it came in 18th place in <i>American Style Magazine</i>â€™s Best Art Town City list, and the <i>Vegetarian Times</i> listed it among the â€œTop 20 Greenest Spots in the Country.â€?  The number of bests cited on the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ci.boulder.co.us/comm/Public%20Affairs%20Internet/Best.htm" title="city of Boulder website">city of Boulder website</a> is truly staggering: over the past five years, Boulder has been praised by <i>Sports Illustrated</i>, <i>Menâ€™s Journal</i>, <i>Animal Wellness Magazine</i>, <i> Outside</i>, <i>Modern Maturity</i>, <i>Self</i>, and <i>Runnerâ€™s World</i>, among others.  According to these best lists that stretch back for over a decade, if youâ€™re a dog, a jogger, a runner, a hiker, a rock climber, a man, a woman, a child, a vegetarian, an elderly person, or single, Boulder is apparently the place to be.  Only out-of-shape, television watching, red-meat-eating, middle-aged ferret owners of indeterminate gender should move elsewhere.<br />
<br />
Boulder is indeed a wonderful place to live.  But does it really merit this lovefest, or is there a cabal of magazine writers colluding with Boulder realtors to keep the housing prices high?  Itâ€™s clear why <i>Money</i> magazine favored Louisville, and <i>Forbes</i> preferred Boulderâ€”<i>Money</i> caters to middle-class people who are looking for ways to stretch their salaries, and <i>Forbes</i> is targeted toward business executives, an audience that fits in well with the new Boulder.  <br />
<br />
Boulderâ€™s rapid evolution into a Front Range Aspen became clear to me when I was taking a look around the NoBo development one dayâ€”judging from all of all the Beamers parked everywhere, it was sort of place where a <i>Forbes</i>-reading single might buy a home.  The development was full of architecturally compelling modernist houses and beautiful people whose children were running around, dressed in designer clothesâ€”one little girl rolling in the grass was wearing a Lilly Pulitzer dress, which I recognized because I had recently stopped in front of a display of them at the mall and pondered just what sort of people dressed their toddlers so extravagantly.  I looked at a flyer for a two-bedroom condo that was selling for almost a half a million dollars and nearly choked.  A pimped-out S.U.V. rolled up next to me and the woman inside flashed me a toothpaste-commercial smile.  â€œAre you looking to buy?â€? she asked, and handed me her realtor business card.  Itâ€™s enough to make a person want to move to Louisville.
